Using the Bay Delta WQ dataset:

  1. For the Water Years 2005-2012, develop a predictive model of the mean monthly Chl-a concentration in the California Bay Delta using other mean monthly water quality variables.

Be sure to show your work, including multiple model comparison (or step models), provide quantification and explain the reasoning behind your final model selection. * Below you will find (1) Data Wrangling, (2) Check for correlation and regression assumptions, (3) A summary and comparison of 4 models developed

Which variables are highly correlated with the others? How did you account for this? * Below, in the (2) check for regression assumptions, you will see a check of highly correlated variables Be sure to demonstrate that you have accounted for all assumptions in your regression. * Assumptions are Identify any badly fitted observations, discuss whether your residuals are following expected patterns, and discuss whether there are any possible explanations for any poorly modeled observations. * Badly fitted observations: Nitrite + Nitrate (Dissolved) + Organic Nitrogen (Dissolved) + Ammonia (Dissolved) Phosphorus (Total) + Ortho-phosphate (Dissolved) - Possible explanations for poor fit: observations are correlated and covered in another observation (like total instead of just dissolved), there is no relationship to Chl-a, data was not properly collected and there actually is a good relationship with Chl-a * Well fitted observations: Kjeldahl Nitrogen (Total) + Oxygen + Temperature - Oxygen and Temperature are highly correlated so I think that this is overfitting * Residuals are found in (3) A summary and comparison of 4 models developed Quantify how much variance in mean monthly Chl-a is explained by the variables you selected. * Variance is shown in (3) A summary and comparison of 4 models developed, the AIC for each variable is calculated in the step(lm()) nested function. * Temperature showed the most explanation for Chl-a prediction * Best model was the EPA model that included Temp, Oxygen, and Kjeldal Nit. - Had the highest adj-R^2 and the lowest AIC

#water year function found: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/40351788/plotting-a-non-standard-year-water-year-with-ggplot2
wtr_yr <- function(dates, start_month=10) {
  # Convert dates into POSIXlt
  dates.posix = as.POSIXlt(dates)
  # Year offset
  offset = ifelse(dates.posix$mon >= start_month - 1, 1, 0)
  # Water year
  adj.year = dates.posix$year + 1900 + offset
  # Return the water year
  adj.year
}

(2) Check for correlation and regression assumptions

Lets check correlation? * Nutrients are all positively (blue) correlated with eachother. * Suspended Solids (total and volatile) are corelated positively * Carbon is correlated * Nitrite and Ammonia are positively correlated (nitrogen) * Conductance is highly correlated with Calcium (ion!!), Cholide (ion!!), and Solids (Total Dissolved) (not sure why that is chemically, could be coincidence?) - Calcium and Chloride are highly positively correlated because they are ions, interesting * Oxygen is highly negatively correlated with Temperature * Secchi Depth and Carbon are natively correlated * Temperature and Ammonia are highly correlated

  • Cholorphyll is highly correlated with
  • oxygen (negative)
  • ammonia (negative)
  • temperature (positive)

Parallel Regression- Parallel regression specifies an additive model, where there is one regression line (for the continuous predictor) which is displaced vertically according to the mean value of the discrete predictor. It hypothesizes that the only effect of the discrete predictor is to adjust the mean, but that the relation between the continuous predictor and the response variable is then the same for all classes of the discrete predictor.

Using your mean monthly water quality dataset for CA WY 2005-2012, create a new discrete value called season, and assign a label to your data for wet season and dry season (you will have decide what constitutes wet and dry). Model the mean monthly Chl-a concentration as a function of season and the water quality variable you idenitifed as MOST important in explaining the variance of Chl-a from question 1.

Model them first separately, then as an additive model, e.g.: lm(Chl-a ~ season) lm(Chl-a ~ my_most_important_variable) lm(Chl-a ~ season + my_most_important_variable) Completed below in Regression Analysis section How much of the variation in Chl-a is explained by season? By your most important variable? By both together? Is the combined model better than individual models? According to the statistics, combined model is better, but not by much. * Combined model vs.Temp adj R^2 is 0.25 vs 0.26 and AIC are both approximately 408 * Since season and temperature are correlated, combining both of them seems like overfitting, so I would say that Temperature is really the better model. Not combined.
